    "answer_id" : 9909417,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Or you could use the modulo operator:</p>\n\n<p><code>(d % 1) == 0</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3786933,
      "reputation" : 9,
      "user_id" : 3144584,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/805fe3d5492aa820ca9df545073396fe?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Salvi94",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3144584/salvi94"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1395160528,
    "creation_date" : 1395160528,
    "answer_id" : 22485524,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>you could try in this way: get the integer value of the double, subtract this from the original double value, define a rounding range and tests if the absolute number of the new double value(without the integer part) is larger or smaller than your defined range. if it is smaller you can intend it it is an integer value. Example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public final double testRange = 0.2;\n\npublic static boolean doubleIsInteger(double d){\n    int i = (int)d;\n    double abs = Math.abs(d-i);\n    return abs &lt;= testRange;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>If you assign to d the value 33.15 the method return true. To have better results you can assign lower values to testRange (as 0.0002) at your discretion.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 7612234,
      "reputation" : 551,
      "user_id" : 5772735,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 56,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/05ecb8eb72a25345af99097b8ddee530?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Sheldon",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5772735/sheldon"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 13,
    "last_activity_date" : 1452663545,
    "last_edit_date" : 1452663545,
    "creation_date" : 1452504634,
    "answer_id" : 34718026,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Try this way,</p>\n\n<pre><code>public static boolean isInteger(double number){\n    return Math.ceil(number) == Math.floor(number); \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>for example:  </p>\n\n<pre><code>Math.ceil(12.9) = 13; Math.floor(12.9) = 12;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>hence <strong>12.9</strong> is <strong>not</strong> integer,  nevertheless </p>\n\n<pre><code> Math.ceil(12.0) = 12; Math.floor(12.0) =12; \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>hence <strong>12.0</strong> is integer</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2334871,
      "reputation" : 2361,
      "user_id" : 2047442,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3fd37ecc867817d2cc40c5973c065709?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "irudyak",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2047442/irudyak"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1475847068,
    "creation_date" : 1475847068,
    "answer_id" : 39918502,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here's a version for <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>    private static boolean isInteger(Double variable) {\n    if (    variable.equals(Math.floor(variable)) &amp;&amp; \n            !Double.isInfinite(variable)          &amp;&amp;\n            !Double.isNaN(variable)               &amp;&amp;\n            variable &lt;= Integer.MAX_VALUE         &amp;&amp;\n            variable &gt;= Integer.MIN_VALUE) {\n        return true;\n    } else {\n        return false;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>To convert <code>Double</code> to <code>Integer</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Integer intVariable = variable.intValue();\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 9347705,
      "reputation" : 1,
      "user_id" : 6938455,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/VqeH4.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "MOHIT GUPTA",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6938455/mohit-gupta"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : -1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1479116677,
    "last_edit_date" : 1479116677,
    "creation_date" : 1479109142,
    "answer_id" : 40583915,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here's a solution:</p>\n\n<pre><code>float var = Your_Value;\nif ((var - Math.floor(var)) == 0.0f)\n{\n    // var is an integer, so do stuff\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 157468,
      "reputation" : 21,
      "user_id" : 2211444,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a2e0320552c2f612f2d16f03136660cc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "edwardsayer",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2211444/edwardsayer"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1488981927,
    "creation_date" : 1488981927,
    "answer_id" : 42673462,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Similar to SkonJeet's answer above, but the performance is better (at least in java):</p>\n\n<pre><code>Double zero = 0d;    \nzero.longValue() == zero.doubleValue()\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6856255,
      "reputation" : 158,
      "user_id" : 5271737,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3330eaa93d2f81a47253ef3e1e42ab0a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "chaeschuechli",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5271737/chaeschuechli"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1498224584,
    "creation_date" : 1498224584,
    "answer_id" : 44722683,
    "question_id" : 9898512,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Personally, I prefer the simple modulo operation solution in the accepted answer.\nUnfortunately, SonarQube doesn't like equality tests with floating points without setting a round precision. So we have tried to find a more compliant solution. Here it is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>if (new BigDecimal(decimalValue).remainder(new BigDecimal(1)).equals(BigDecimal.ZERO)) {\n    // no decimal places\n} else {\n    // decimal places\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><code>Remainder(BigDecimal)</code> returns a <code>BigDecimal</code> whose value is <code>(this % divisor)</code>. If this one's equal to zero, we know there is no floating point.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3113945,
      "reputation" : 1125,
      "user_id" : 2635146,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/IIhYu.gif?s=256",
